  "text": "The JCE (Java Cryptography Extension) provider architecture in OpenJDK follows a pluggable design pattern:\n\n1. **Provider.java** (src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Provider.java): Defines the abstract Provider class that serves as the base for all cryptographic service providers. It contains the inner Service class (lines 1500+) which represents a service offered by a provider, including type (e.g., \"Cipher\"), algorithm name, implementation class name, and attributes.\n\n2. **Security.java** (src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Security.java): The Security class centralizes management of all registered providers. It loads the master security properties file from conf/security/java.security (line 140), maintains a provider list, and provides static methods getProvider(name) and getProviders() to retrieve providers. The SecPropLoader inner class handles loading security properties from the java.security configuration file.\n\n3. **SunJCE.java** (src/java.base/share/classes/com/sun/crypto/provider/SunJCE.java): The SunJCE provider implementation class extends Provider. Its constructor (line 124) registers cryptographic algorithms including RSA, DES, Triple DES, AES, Blowfish, ARCFOUR, RC2, PBE, Diffie-Hellman, HMAC, ChaCha20, DHKEM, and ML-KEM. It uses the putService() method to register Service instances with the provider.\n\n4. **Cipher.java** (src/java.base/share/classes/javax/crypto/Cipher.java): The Cipher factory class provides three getInstance() overloads (lines 538, 637, 707) to create Cipher instances. The getInstance(String transformation) method (line 538) iterates through all registered providers using GetInstance.getServices() to find a provider supporting the transformation. The getInstance(String transformation, String provider) method (line 637) uses Security.getProvider(name) to get a specific provider. The getInstance(String transformation, Provider provider) method (line 707) directly queries the provider's getService() method.\n\n5. **java.security** (src/java.base/share/conf/security/java.security): The master security properties file that statically configures providers using security.provider.<n>=<providerName> entries. Line 100 lists SunJCE as a registered provider, and the file documents the provider registration mechanism and preference order (line 74-75).\n\nThe call chain flows: Cipher.getInstance() → Security.getProvider() or provider.getService() → Provider.Service → implementation class instantiation via reflection."
}

